		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/12/opinion/nyto-putin/nyto-putin-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/12/opinion/nyto-putin/nyto-putin-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/12/opinion/nyto-putin/nyto-putin-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003301053" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Pool Photo by Alexey Druzhinin</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/12/12/does-the-u-s-need-a-new-approach-to-putin/" data-title="Does the U.S. Need a New Approach to Putin?" data-description="Some think that the West is pushing too hard on Russia â and missing a complete picture of Putinâs motivations. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âConventional wisdom â or conventional hope â among many of the people who would like to see the end of the Putin regime has long been that a turn for the worse in the Russian economy will make the moneyed elite turn on the Russian president,â Masha Gessen writes at <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/11/opinion/masha-gessen-the-myth-of-the-russian-oligarchs.html?_r=0">The New York Times</a>. âJournalists, pundits and Mr. Putinâs political opponents in Russia have predicted that Western sanctions and the economic disaster they hasten will result in a coup d&#8217;Ã©tat staged by oligarchs. There is just one problem with that argument: There are no oligarchs anymore.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Like Ms. Gessen, some observers are questioning the Westâs confrontational approach to Vladimir V. Putin and Russia. Still others are questioning the wisdom ofÂ acting without fully understanding Mr. Putin and his motivation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At <a href="//www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/dont-risk-war-with-russia/">The American Conservative</a>, Philip Giraldi, the executive director of the Council for the National Interest, writes that âWashington is slipping into a new and completely unnecessary confrontation with Moscow.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In his view, this confrontation is conducted overtly â through sanctions and resolutions by Congress â and covertly â through the funding and training of opposition groups that takes place outside of the country being targeted.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe United States has a great deal to lose if Russia chooses to go tit-for-tat in responding to both the overt and secretive attacks on its economy,â Mr. Giraldi writes. âMoscow has been cooperative with both Washington and the Europeans regarding tracking the financing of terrorist groups, proliferators, and drug cartels. It will be unlikely to continue that cooperation if it perceives a Western willingness to act against its own financial institutions and economy.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He adds, âUsing both open and hidden initiatives to push Russia into a corner from which it cannot escape is not good policyâ and may be âdisastrous for all parties involved.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At <a href="//www.lowyinterpreter.org/post/2014/12/08/Time-for-West-to-re-evaluate-its-whole-approach-to-Russia.aspx?COLLCC=2389016564&amp;COLLCC=3478916785&amp;">The Interpreter</a>, a blog published by the Lowy Institute for International Policy in Sydney, Matthew Sussex offers a blueprint for the West to re-evaluate its approach to Russia.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf the U.S. and E.U. lose Russia, they risk driving it completely toward China and thereby recreating bipolarism in a messy globalized environment,â he writes. âThe West already faces an uncomfortable reality: its own normative vision of democratic individualism will have to compete with other narratives seeking to shape legal, institutional and trading arrangements.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Sussex offers an alternative: âmaneuver Russia into a âpivotâ position between East and West. That would allow Moscow to sell its policies to domestic audiences via exceptionalism and great power imagery; it would ensure that energy and resources continue to flow; and it will turn Russia into a massive buffer zone between China and the transatlantic space.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As it happens, Mr. Sussex says, this is âprecisely what the Kremlin wants, too.â Russia does not want to become âChinaâs mine and petrol pump.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt is better to have Russia as a part-time partner than a recurring problem to be managed,â Mr. Sussex adds. To create such a partnership, he says, the West must recognize that Russia will not become a liberal democracy anytime soon. And he believes âEuropean security structures are in urgent need of renovation,â and that any reform must be one âthat Russia can join on an equal footing.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Similarly, an editorial in <a href="//www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/1658243/russia-and-west-need-each-other">South China Morning Post</a> identifies a range of economic challenges for Russia, especially on its reliance on energy, and states, âRussia and the West need one another.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For other observers, the West does not bring to its relations with Mr. Putin a clear understanding of that leaderâs motivation in the first place.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Kirill Kovalenko at <a href="//thediplomat.com/2014/12/why-no-one-gets-russia/">The Diplomat</a> suggests that, in considering Russia, observers need to consider its âculture and public consciousnessâ and its exceptionalism: âIt is an important facet for understanding how the nation considers itself as partaking in a unique destiny and that its special status is necessarily conjoined with elements of, not necessarily freedom and prosperity, but suffering and power.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Noting the âkeen historical awareness that continues to be apparentâ in Russian foreign policy, Mr. Kovalenko adds, âan analysis that anticipates a fatalistic, economics-based interpretation of a Russia delegated to the historical sidelines misses an important cultural factor that drives the countryâs continued insistence on trying to punch above its weight.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But at <a href="//www.europeanvoice.com/other-voices/why-did-putin-turn/">European Voice</a>, Harold James, a history professor at Princeton, thinks that the focus on âa deep exploration of the Russian soulâ is misguided. In his view, Mr. Putin shifted from a modernizing, conciliatory, pro-Western stance to âaggressive revisionismâ not because he felt encircled or because he has become irrational. Instead, according to Mr. James, Mr. Putin identified an opportunity for emerging economies â Brazil, India, China and Russia â to âprovide an alternative to what he viewed as an arbitrary unipolar world order.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In this view, the financial crisis confirmed for Mr. Putin that âthe days of American global dominance were over.â So instead of cooperation with the âlogical of global capitalism,â Russia saw its best option was âto cooperate with other countries that had adopted a similar model of state-centered capitalism, especially China.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Political developments â the Arab Spring, Obamaâs scaling back of American commitments abroad â allowed Mr. Putin âto project himselfâ as a âcredible proponent of geopolitical pragmatism.â And Europeâs muddled reaction to the debt crisis and its ambivalence to the European Union gave the Kremlin âadditional ammunition.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âPutinâs belief that the economic crisis was causing the West to disintegrate aligns with traditional Soviet geopolitical thinking,â Mr. James concludes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At <a href="//www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/russia-identity-foreign-policy-by-shlomo-ben-ami-2014-12">Project Syndicate</a>, Shlomo Ben-Ami, a former Israeli foreign minister, focuses on Russiaâs identity after the Cold War: âRussia must pursue and develop its unique identity â with Putin leading the way. Securing a place for Russia in a new world order is integral to establishing such an identity.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He notes that Mr. Putin has maximized the foreign-policy value of Russiaâs energy resources. He adds, âPutinâs defiance of U.S. hegemony could attract support from countries and peoples worldwide that resent American-imposed values and norms.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And he cautions against the reliance on sanctions: âThough this approach could weaken Putinâs legitimacy by limiting his ability to deliver economic prosperity, it could also result in an anti-Western nationalist backlashâ and âcan be presented as a blessing, forcing the Kremlin to diversify Russiaâs commodities-based economy.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He concludes: âRussia does not need to upend the existing global order; it simply needs to find its place. And the U.S. must let it.â</p>
	</div>
